And as I said,
we'll have a session following

00:15:23.750 --> 00:15:27.510
this one where we're going to go
into great detail about how you

00:15:27.510 --> 00:15:29.870
can transition your UI to iOS 7.

00:15:29.880 --> 00:15:34.000
We're going to talk about icon design,
line thickness, going edge-to-edge,

00:15:34.110 --> 00:15:37.310
improving legibility of text,
all kinds of things that

00:15:37.310 --> 00:15:39.010
you need to know about.

00:15:39.370 --> 00:15:43.000
That you may have read about but didn't
necessarily know how to approach.

00:15:43.080 --> 00:15:44.900
And so we'll go into that detail.

00:15:44.900 --> 00:15:48.230
Now,
in addition to the new UI with iOS 7,

00:15:48.230 --> 00:15:53.580
there's a whole lot of new technology
for you to use in the iOS 7 SDK.

00:15:53.580 --> 00:15:56.920
With every one of the releases
of iOS over the years,

00:15:57.030 --> 00:16:01.310
we've come out with an SDK that
has new technology for you to use.

00:16:01.360 --> 00:16:04.290
And this technology comes in the
form of new frameworks or major

00:16:04.350 --> 00:16:06.230
enhancements to existing frameworks.

00:16:06.300 --> 00:16:08.770
And none of this is new news to you.

00:16:09.270 --> 00:16:11.360
So many of you are
experienced developers.

00:16:11.760 --> 00:16:14.000
Pretty much everybody in the room
has got an app on the App Store,

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:14.890
and so you know this.

00:16:14.980 --> 00:16:19.650
But I just want to stay high level for a
moment in this kickoff session and just

00:16:19.650 --> 00:16:23.940
remind you that it's in the SDK that
you have the building blocks that

00:16:24.050 --> 00:16:26.710
you're going to use to build your app,
obviously.

00:16:26.920 --> 00:16:30.550
But it's with these building
blocks that you can choose.

00:16:30.690 --> 00:16:33.860
It's how you choose to assemble
these building blocks that makes

00:16:33.860 --> 00:16:37.510
the difference between an average
app and an app that really shines.

00:16:49.820 --> 00:16:50.120
And on top of the new UI and
the new technology in the SDK,

00:16:50.120 --> 00:16:50.250
there's a whole new generation
of hardware that's just come out.

00:16:50.250 --> 00:16:51.630
And most recently, we introduced the iPad
Air and the iPad Mini,

00:16:51.790 --> 00:16:53.880
both of them with Retina display.

00:16:53.920 --> 00:16:56.240
And so now every single
one of our iOS devices,

00:16:56.240 --> 00:16:58.080
I believe, is Retina-enabled.

00:17:01.540 --> 00:17:12.790
And these new devices
are incredibly powerful.

00:17:12.790 --> 00:17:12.790
And they're built around the new
A7 chip with 64-bit architecture.

00:17:12.790 --> 00:17:12.790
And they've got the
M7 motion coprocessor.

00:17:14.060 --> 00:17:16.910
And on top of that,
we introduced the iPhone 5s,

00:17:16.910 --> 00:17:20.590
which preceded the iPad
Air and the iPad mini Retina.

00:17:21.020 --> 00:17:25.790
But it's another powerful iOS device,
and it's built on the same A7 chip,

00:17:26.040 --> 00:17:29.940
obviously, and it features the
Touch ID fingerprint sensor,

00:17:30.020 --> 00:17:33.960
which adds a whole new level
of convenience while also being

00:17:34.080 --> 00:17:36.200
more secure at the same time.

00:17:36.370 --> 00:17:41.460
And all of these things combine,
all of these powerful new devices

00:17:41.620 --> 00:17:46.170
and the release of iOS 7 combine
to create and form a new foundation

00:17:46.740 --> 00:17:48.620
for next-generation apps.

00:17:48.620 --> 00:17:52.710
And helping you get the most
out of this new foundation

00:17:52.710 --> 00:17:55.000
is what today is all about.

00:17:55.190 --> 00:17:59.180
We want to help you understand
what a next-generation app

00:17:59.180 --> 00:18:01.010
is and how to build one.

00:18:02.830 --> 00:18:07.260
So let's talk about what
a next-generation app is.

00:18:07.390 --> 00:18:11.340
First and foremost, next-generation apps,
of course, have to be great.

00:18:11.380 --> 00:18:14.690
And I talk about great apps all the time.

00:18:14.740 --> 00:18:18.780
If you've ever been to a
Tech Talk where I've kicked off the

00:18:18.890 --> 00:18:23.460
session before or kicked off before,
I've talked about great apps.

00:18:23.500 --> 00:18:27.350
And yet, over and over,
as I meet with developers,

00:18:27.580 --> 00:18:32.850
people still don't have a good handle
on what the definition of great is.

00:18:32.950 --> 00:18:35.780
So what makes a great app?

00:18:37.040 --> 00:18:40.420
Well, it's not just the
technology that you adopt.

00:18:40.430 --> 00:18:43.840
It's not just the
APIs that you integrate.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:53.000
[ Transcript missing ]

00:18:53.490 --> 00:18:58.000
What people care about is
what your app lets them do.

00:18:58.160 --> 00:19:02.470
People care about the solution,
not so much the collection of

00:19:02.470 --> 00:19:04.660
technologies or the features per se.

00:19:04.960 --> 00:19:09.000
And so great apps offer
a fantastic solution.

00:19:09.060 --> 00:19:11.450
In other words,
developing a great app is really all

00:19:11.470 --> 00:19:17.070
about making something that's intuitive,
engaging, beautiful, and very,

00:19:17.120 --> 00:19:18.800
very useful.

00:19:20.340 --> 00:19:23.670
Now, there are a lot of characteristics
and traits that make an app great.

00:19:23.770 --> 00:19:25.380
And I've talked about these before.

00:19:25.400 --> 00:19:28.700
There's a video on the developer
website that's somewhat dated now,

00:19:28.700 --> 00:19:32.680
but where I go into depth
on many of these terms.

00:19:32.730 --> 00:19:36.420
And we've worked with
