00:45:12.230 --> 00:45:17.560
And using these multitasking
API means that your app is always

00:45:17.560 --> 00:45:20.770
ready for when people want to use it.

00:45:20.850 --> 00:45:22.490
And this is key.

00:45:24.140 --> 00:45:24.630
Right?

00:45:24.630 --> 00:45:28.150
We're all familiar with this,
where iOS 7 is a great app switcher,

00:45:28.170 --> 00:45:32.080
and people can see a snapshot of your
app even when it's not the frontmost app,

00:45:32.080 --> 00:45:32.820
right?

00:45:32.820 --> 00:45:35.430
We double tap the home button,
we get in there, we can move around.

00:45:35.480 --> 00:45:39.770
And what's important here is that
you want to make sure that the

00:45:39.770 --> 00:45:44.770
snapshot of your app is up to date,
so that when someone taps on your app,

00:45:44.780 --> 00:45:50.130
the snapshot matches what will happen
when the app comes to life again.

00:45:50.140 --> 00:45:52.800
And most importantly,
you want to be up to date.

00:45:54.130 --> 00:45:56.030
When they get into your app,
you don't want to have and many of

00:45:56.030 --> 00:45:59.620
you saw this probably the very first
time you ran your app on iOS 7,

00:45:59.860 --> 00:46:03.750
you don't want to have just your snapshot
to be a white screen with nothing on it.

00:46:04.410 --> 00:46:06.460
Customers don't know then
what's going on in the app,

00:46:06.460 --> 00:46:08.030
and it's not a great experience.

00:46:08.110 --> 00:46:11.170
So being ready using the
multitasking API correctly is

00:46:11.170 --> 00:46:16.220
really important for being up to
date for customers within your app.

00:46:16.920 --> 00:46:19.420
And iOS 7 does a lot of things
around multitasking that are

00:46:19.420 --> 00:46:21.420
beneficial to you as a developer,
right?

00:46:21.900 --> 00:46:22.980
We do intelligent scheduling.

00:46:23.560 --> 00:46:24.850
And notice when your
app is typically used,

00:46:24.930 --> 00:46:28.480
and we will give it background
cycles based on that usage pattern.

00:46:29.120 --> 00:46:31.880
We take advantage of times when
the device is powered up and let

00:46:31.880 --> 00:46:33.680
your app do opportunistic updates.

00:46:34.700 --> 00:46:37.300
And iOS 7 responds to push notifications.

00:46:38.040 --> 00:46:41.580
So as a trigger to give your app time
to go and fetch data that's needed

00:46:41.590 --> 00:46:43.600
based on that push notification.

00:46:44.340 --> 00:46:47.040
And so there's no more
waiting for screens to reload,

00:46:47.040 --> 00:46:50.660
or at least there shouldn't be any
more waiting for screens to reload.

00:46:51.160 --> 00:46:53.120
If you're taking advantage
of multitasking on iOS.

00:46:53.140 --> 00:46:56.980
correctly.

00:46:57.380 --> 00:47:02.420
The way to do this is to take
advantage of the three API that exist.

00:47:02.500 --> 00:47:05.550
There's background fetch,
where we will run your app periodically

00:47:05.550 --> 00:47:10.080
so that you can pull new data down
and update your UI accordingly.

00:47:10.150 --> 00:47:13.340
There's remote notifications,
where we'll run your app in response

00:47:13.490 --> 00:47:16.960
to a push notification so that you
can update your content on demand

00:47:16.960 --> 00:47:21.100
versus having to poll for information,
which is very inefficient.

00:47:21.140 --> 00:47:23.220
And lastly,
there are background transfers,

00:47:23.290 --> 00:47:28.040
where iOS will upload or download data
in the background on behalf of your app,

00:47:28.070 --> 00:47:30.230
even if it isn't running.

00:47:30.350 --> 00:47:33.920
So those three API are very important
for giving a great experience.

00:47:33.980 --> 00:47:38.550
And we will talk more about these
API in greater depth today in one

00:47:38.550 --> 00:47:40.880
of our sessions this afternoon.

00:47:41.040 --> 00:47:44.080
And since you've got new opportunities,
though,

00:47:44.170 --> 00:47:48.230
on iOS 7 for your app to be running,
it's even more important than

00:47:48.230 --> 00:47:52.660
ever that you are power smart when
you do your background updates.

00:47:52.660 --> 00:47:56.090
So let's just talk about
power smart for a moment.

00:47:56.160 --> 00:47:59.610
So first, using the network requires
powering the antennas,

00:47:59.610 --> 00:48:04.260
regardless of whether you're using Wi-Fi,
cellular, or Bluetooth, right?

00:48:04.260 --> 00:48:06.870
If we turn on a radio,
it takes power from the battery.

00:48:06.900 --> 00:48:10.060
So be sure to optimize your networking.

00:48:11.230 --> 00:48:15.550
not only be transmitting the
least amount of data as necessary,

00:48:15.900 --> 00:48:31.500
[ Transcript missing ]

00:48:31.820 --> 00:48:33.750
Secondly,
when you want to know the type of

00:48:33.750 --> 00:48:38.470
activity that the user is engaged in,
use the M7 processor and the

00:48:38.590 --> 00:48:43.150
core motion APIs rather than
doing things manually on the CPU,

00:48:43.150 --> 00:48:45.260
as we talked about before.

00:48:45.650 --> 00:48:48.240
If you are showing
information in real time,

00:48:48.280 --> 00:48:51.690
you can get a constant feed
but only capture the data

00:48:51.700 --> 00:48:53.590
from the M7 when you need it.

00:48:53.700 --> 00:48:57.720
And lastly,
you can always query the M7 later

00:48:57.720 --> 00:49:01.980
by date range so that you don't
have to constantly be updating

00:49:01.980 --> 00:49:03.980
information using the CPU.

00:49:03.980 --> 00:49:09.270
So there's just new ways of doing things
with M7 and new ways of querying the

00:49:09.430 --> 00:49:14.430
system that really prevent having to
wake up the system radios and wake up

00:49:14.430 --> 00:49:17.970
the hardware in ways that you used to.

00:49:18.530 --> 00:49:21.580
And thirdly,
as far as being power smart is concerned,

00:49:21.580 --> 00:49:25.110
you need to be power smart
when using location services.

00:49:25.110 --> 00:49:29.910
The core location framework relies on
radios to determine the user's location.

00:49:30.170 --> 00:49:31.250
Obviously, right?

00:49:31.270 --> 00:49:34.680
We're turning on the radios
to determine Wi-Fi location,

00:49:34.780 --> 00:49:37.900
to find cell towers,
all of these kinds of things.

00:49:37.960 --> 00:49:40.570
So only use these services when needed.

00:49:40.570 --> 00:49:44.660
This will allow us to turn off the
radios in order to save power when

00:49:44.660 --> 00:49:47.580
you're not tracking the user's location.

00:49:48.510 --> 00:49:51.750
And be sure to use the right service
for the experience that you need.

00:49:51.800 --> 00:49:55.460
For example, if you only need to know
what city a person is in,

00:49:55.460 --> 00:49:59.300
you can do that without requiring
the finest level of accuracy,

00:49:59.300 --> 00:50:01.260
which would use more power.

00:50:01.270 --> 00:50:05.810
So if you just need to know the city,
then don't track down to the meter,

00:50:05.810 --> 00:50:10.340
which is just far more burdensome on
the system and requires the radios to

00:50:10.430 --> 00:50:13.010
be far more active using more power.

00:50:13.020 --> 00:50:17.460
So that's multitasking in iOS 7,
which allows your app to always

00:50:17.460 --> 00:50:21.320
be ready for when people need it,
and some tips on being power smart

00:50:21.320 --> 00:50:24.210
relative to running in the background
