00:50:24.310 --> 00:50:25.780
are capable and possible there.

00:50:25.800 --> 00:50:31.720
And last, but certainly not least,
a next generation app needs to be secure.

00:50:34.420 --> 00:50:37.460
More and more users are setting
a passcode on their devices,

00:50:37.460 --> 00:50:41.420
and on iPhone 5s,
Touch ID does away with the need for the

00:50:41.490 --> 00:50:43.380
passcode most of the time for many users.

00:50:43.420 --> 00:50:47.870
And since all of our current
devices support hardware encryption,

00:50:47.870 --> 00:50:51.780
when the passcode is set,
data protection is enabled.

00:50:54.300 --> 00:50:57.200
And if you're not aware of
how data protection works or

00:50:57.200 --> 00:51:01.180
what it means to your app,
today is the day to learn

00:51:01.180 --> 00:51:03.540
about how this all works.

00:51:03.960 --> 00:51:06.630
I mean,
data protection will encrypt data on disk

00:51:06.780 --> 00:51:09.900
using keys based on the user's passcode.

00:51:09.970 --> 00:51:15.190
And when an iOS device locks,
we throw away these keys and may no

00:51:15.190 --> 00:51:18.000
longer be able to decrypt the data.

00:51:18.040 --> 00:51:22.520
By default, that would include keychain
items and files in some cases.

00:51:22.720 --> 00:51:26.140
And with the new
multitasking APIs in iOS 7,

00:51:26.160 --> 00:51:29.480
your app may be allowed to run
not only in the background,

00:51:29.480 --> 00:51:32.320
but also when the device is locked.

00:51:32.830 --> 00:51:37.600
And this can be a problem for you,
for example, if you want to update your

00:51:37.600 --> 00:51:39.090
app in the background.

00:51:40.280 --> 00:51:44.800
You may need to access credentials
in order to log into your server,

00:51:44.880 --> 00:51:48.280
but if the device is locked,
you might not be able to

00:51:48.280 --> 00:51:50.940
get to those credentials.

00:51:51.030 --> 00:51:55.680
So it's really important to understand
how you should approach this situation.

00:51:56.130 --> 00:51:59.260
And while data protection is important
for securing data on the device,

00:51:59.260 --> 00:52:03.180
it's equally important that you
use the latest best practices when

00:52:03.260 --> 00:52:05.820
you transmit data over the network.

00:52:05.910 --> 00:52:10.900
Be sure that you're using secure
protocols and verifying certificates.

00:52:10.900 --> 00:52:14.690
Whenever possible,
hash sensitive data and always

00:52:14.690 --> 00:52:17.050
respect your user's privacy.

00:52:17.100 --> 00:52:20.710
